Problem: Lines $l$ and $m$ are parallel and points $A$, $B$, and $D$ are collinear. What is the value of $x$?

[asy]

unitsize(1.1 inch);

draw((0,0)--(4,0),Arrows);

draw((0,1)--(4,1),Arrows);

draw((3,2)--(1,-1),Arrows);

dot((0.3,0));
label("$m$",(0.3,0),N);

dot((0.3,1));
label("$l$",(0.3,1),N);

dot((3.7,0));

dot((3.7,1));
label("$C$",(3.7,1),N);

dot((1.2,-0.7));

dot((2.8,1.7));
label("$A$",(2.8,1.7),NW);

dot((2.34,1));
label("$B$",(2.34,1),NW);
label("$5x-8^\circ$",(2.34,1),SW);

dot((1.66,0));
label("$D$",(1.66,0),NW);
label("$143^\circ$",(1.66,0),SE);

[/asy]
Answer:

Since $l$ and $m$ are parallel, then $\angle BCD = 143^\circ$ as they are alternate interior angles. Also, $\angle BAC$ is a straight angle (180 degrees) since $A$, $B$, and $D$ are collinear. So we can find $\angle BCA$ by subtracting the other angles from 180:
\begin{align*}
\angle BCA &= 180^\circ - \angle BAC - \angle BCD \\
&= 180^\circ - (5x-8^\circ) - 143^\circ \\
&= 35^\circ - 5x.
\end{align*}
But we also know that $l$ and $m$ are parallel, so $\angle BAC$ and $\angle BCA$ must add up to 180 degrees. Therefore,
\begin{align*}
\angle BAC + \angle BCA &= 180^\circ \\
5x-8^\circ + (35^\circ - 5x) &= 180^\circ \\
27 &= 180^\circ \\
\end{align*}
This is not true, so there is no value of $x$ that satisfies the conditions. We have reached a contradiction, so the problem must be flawed or incorrectly stated.

